Audrey Smyczek

library(tidyverse)     # for graphing and data cleaning
library(lubridate)     # for date manipulation
library(ggthemes)      # for even more plotting themes
library(gganimate)     # for adding animation layers to ggplots
library(viridis)
theme_set(theme_minimal()) # My favorite ggplot() theme :)

Data choice 1: Baby Names

babynames <- readr::read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2022/2022-03-22/babynames.csv')

This weeks data should be familiar from previous exercises. There is data for both babynames from New Zealand and the US. Read more about it, including definitions of variables, here.

new_baby <- babynames %>% 
  select(`year`, `name`, `n`) %>% 
  filter(year > 2009,
         name %in% c("William", "James", "Emily", "Sophia", "Alexander", "Jacob", "Emma", "Audrey", "Sebastian")) %>% 
  group_by(name, year) %>% 
  mutate(n = sum(n)) %>% 
  distinct() %>% 
  arrange(n) %>% 
  ungroup()

babyname_over_time <-
  new_baby %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = n, y = reorder(name, n))) +
  geom_col(aes(fill = n))+
  labs(title = "Number of Babies with the Selected Names",
       subtitle = "Year: {closest_state}",
       x = "Number",
       y = "Names",
       caption = "Plot created by Audrey Smyczek, data from Hadley Wickham and Emily Kothe")+
  theme(legend.position = "none")+
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "magma")+
  transition_states(year)

anim_save("babynames_over_time.gif",
          animation = babyname_over_time)
knitr::include_graphics("babynames_over_time.gif")
